For the sake of simplicity and clarity, we'll consider a one-dimensional system. This code demonstrates the behavior of the linearized system at steady-state values with set parameter values. Here is the MATLAB code:

``` matlab
% Parameters
L = 10;  % Length of the domain
D = 1;   % Diffusion coefficient for population
C = 1;   % Diffusion coefficient for information density
r = 0.1; % Growth rate
K = 100; % Carrying capacity
a = 0.01;% Information density effect

% Discretization
Nx = 100; % Number of grid points in x
dx = L/Nx;
x = linspace(0, L, Nx);

% Steady state values
y_star = K;
x_star = 0;

% Compute the Laplacian operator
Lap = sparse(Nx, Nx);
for i = 1:Nx
    j = i-1;
    if j==0
        j = Nx;
    end
    Lap(i, j) = 1;

    j = i+1;
    if j > Nx
        j = 1;
    end
    Lap(i, j) = 1;

    Lap(i, i) = -2;
end
Lap = Lap / dx^2;

% Evaluation of partial derivatives at steady state values
dfdy_star = -r * y_star / K;
dfdx_star = a;

dgdy_star = 0;
dgdx_star = r;

% Linearized system matrix
A = [D*Lap + dfdy_star*speye(Nx), dfdx_star*speye(Nx);
    dgdy_star*speye(Nx), C*Lap + dgdx_star*speye(Nx)];

% Compute eigenvalues
e = eig(full(A));

% Plot eigenvalues
real_e = real(e);
imag_e = imag(e);

figure;
plot(real_e, imag_e, 'o');
xlabel('Real part');
ylabel('Imaginary part');
title('Eigenvalues of the linearized system');
grid on;

% Check stability condition
if all(real_e < 0)
    disp('The system is stable.');
else
    disp('The system is unstable.');
end
```

